default&#xa0;default2: Introduction:default2.1: I am a retired mechanical engineer from the nuclear power industry.  After working at Longannet, Hunterston 'B' and Heysham Power Stations, I joined the staff of 
defaulta small engineering team preparing and evaluating nuclear safety cases in support of nuclear power stations in the south-east of England.
default&#xa0;
default2.2: In June, I was cold-called by a company who wished to sell me a heat pump.  I agreed to accept a sales engineer's visit to my house.  When the sales engineer asked for my order, I responded with 'due diligence first'.  Due diligence continues.  
default&#xa0;
default2.3:
default The insights gained allow me to address the committee's following questions :-
default2.3.1: 
default              
defaultQ1 - Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully? 
default              
defaultA1 - Because it has got the fundamental science wrong.
default&#xa0;
default2.3.2: 
default              
defaultQ2 - What are the relative merits o
defaultf using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?
default              
defaultA2 – Capacity balance should be about 90% gas/fossil fuel, 10% air-to-air heat pump.  Heat production balance is then about 10% gas/foss
defaultil fuel, 90% air-to-air heat pump. Use of gas/fossil fuel occurs when it is as efficient as or more efficient than the heat pump, taken over the full CCGT/grid/distribution/heat pump route (i.e. at sub-zero temperatures).  This balance has the minimum Carb
defaulton burn and the minimum capital cost over the generation/grid/distribution/heat pump route as compared to the boiler route.
default&#xa0;
default2.3.3: 
default              
defaultQ3 - How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?
default              
defaultA3 – In respect of heat pumps, disastrous unless totall
defaulty redrafted.
