default3: Facts:default3.1:  Carnot's Law:defaultCarnot's Law states that the theoretical maximum efficiency of a heat pump is equal to Thot/(Thot-Tcold) where temperatures are stated in degrees absolute (e.g. fr
defaulteezing is 273C and boiling is 373C)
defaultCOP 5/30=(273+30)/(30-5)=303/25=12.12
defaultCOP 5/60=(273+60)/(60-5)=333/55=6.05
default12.12/6.05= 2
defaultThis is the basis of the statement that air-to-air pumps that blow air at 30C are twice as efficient as air-to-water pumps that use
default hot wet radiators at 60C.
default&#xa0;
defaultReal heat pumps deliver less than the theoretical maximum, perhaps 0.4 to 0.6 forms the main range.  Part load coefficients at loads below 50% start to deteriorate rapidly to 0 at 0% part load  e.g. If the theoretical Carnot eff
defaulticiency is x, the pump factor is 0.5 and the part load factor is also 0.5, then the overall efficiency of the pump is x/4.  The Carnot efficiency of resistive heating is 1.0.
default&#xa0;default______________________________________________
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default3.2:  I2R Losses in defaultTransformers and Cables on the National Grid and Distribution NetworksdefaultCurrent losses on the National Grid are about 3%.
defaultCurrent losses on the Distribution Network are about 8%.
default&#xa0;
defaultIf 8.6 million homes have 10kW(electrical) heat pumps fitted, then this is a 
defaultcapacity demand on the grid system of 86GW, approximately equal to the currently installed capacity.
defaultIf this doubles line and transformer currents, then the I2R losses quadruple to (3+8)*4=44%.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe I2R losses heat the lines and transformers which have the
defaultrmal overload protection.  At some point the protection will start 'tripping' and supply breakers will open.  The result may be blackouts.
default&#xa0;
defaultMajor reinforcement of the grid and distribution networks would be needed, right down to the 415V transformers that 
defaultsupply houses.  If the cabling needs reinforcing, that means digging up the roads.
default&#xa0;
defaultMy current domestic electrical load is about 10kWh per day, all year.
defaultMy current domestic gas load is an average of about 100kWh per day during winter and 10kWh per day in 
defaultthe summer.
default&#xa0;
defaultTransferring all my winter demand to the electrical supply will increase my peak demand on the electrical supply by a factor of about 11.  I have no reason to think that my consumption is atypical.
default&#xa0;
default10/11ths of that higher electrical load will
default be continuous over the colder days, with peaks in the remaining 1/11 that mirror the current 24 hour demand curve of the grid.  When a pre-existing grid peak combines with a heat pump load peak, then what is the demand on, 1: local supply transformers, an
defaultd 2:  power station capacity?
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is the local supply transformers that receive the greatest increase.  The power station load rises by a factor of 2 but the domestic supply transformers experience an 11 fold rise.  Local supply transformers are sized 'sto
defaultchastically'; they are already too small for all the total installed load in the attached houses and presumably their supply cables are similarly sized.  An 11-fold increase in cable cross-sections and transformers is predicted on the 415V system.  I2R los
defaultses have a major effect on the draft RHI policy.  There has to be a better way and there is:  the 1kWe capacity air-to-air heat pump, installed one per house.
default______________________________________________
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default3.3: Efficiencies and Coefficients of defaultPerformance (COPs)defaultThe draft domestic RHI policy is about the comparative efficiency of two routes :-
default1:  generator/grid/distribution/heat pump, and
default2:  domestic boiler.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe best gas turbine generators achieve about 0.65 efficiency
defaultBig steam turbines 
defaultachieve about 0.35
defaultGrid losses are currently about 3%, so 0.97
defaultDistribution losses are currently about 8%, so 0.92
default&#xa0;
defaultThe efficiency of domestic pure resistive heating from :-
default1: gas generated grid supplied electricity is .65x.97x.92x1.0
default              
default= 0.58
default2: steam turb
defaultine, grid supplied electricity is .35x.97x.92x1.0
default              
default= 0.31
default&#xa0;
defaultThe highest(65%) generation efficiencies come from CCGT plant; the highest heat pump headline COPs(5.5+) come from air-to-air pumps .
default&#xa0;
defaultClearly, the most efficient overall system requires the highest
default generation efficiencies, coupled with the lowest grid and distribution losses and the heat pumps with the highest COPs (.65x.97x.92x5.5= 3.19).  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe poorest system is steam turbine electricity, through overloaded grid/distribution to a resistive load (.
default35x.86x.72x1.0
default              
default= 0.22).
default&#xa0;
defaultThe ratio of best to worst is 3.19/0.22=14.5. 
default It is a very large number and graphically illustrates the potential benefit of heat pumps, PROVIDED  that ALL the technology involved is operating at optimum efficiency.   default1: Generatidefaulton, default2: grid, default3: distribution, and default4: heat pump defaultefficiencies have to be individually maximised to achieved the combined desired result, whilst noting that the gas grid can help in a major way.default______________________________________________
